      <a href="/guides/" class="hover:text-emerald-400">Guides</a>
      <span class="mx-2">›</span>
      <span class="text-neutral-400">Best English Courses for Travel</span>
    </nav>
  </div>
<article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-12">
  <div class="mb-8">
    <span class="text-sm text-gray-400">Guide · Updated April 2026</span>
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold mt-1 mb-4">5 Best English Courses for Travel: Your Ticket to the World</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-400">Master the essential phrases and confidence you need to navigate any destination with ease.</p>
  </div>

  <div class="bg-blue-900/30 border border-blue-700/50 rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
    <div class="flex items-center justify-between flex-wrap gap-3">
      <div>
        <p class="font-bold text-lg text-blue-200">Top Choice</p>
        <p class="text-2xl md:text-3xl font-bold text-blue-100">iTalki (Travel Specialists)</p>
      </div>
      <div class="text-left md:text-right">
        <p class="text-sm text-gray-400">Best for</p>
        <p class="font-semibold text-blue-200">Real-world Practice</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">Why General English Isn't Enough for Travel</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">When you are standing at a train station in London or checking into a hotel in New York, you do not need to know complex grammar rules. You need functional language. Travel English focuses on survival skills: ordering food, asking for directions, handling transport delays, and making small talk with locals.</p>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">It also requires <strong>listening resilience</strong>. A London cabbie, a New York waiter, and a Sydney Uber driver all speak different versions of English. Travel courses that only expose you to one accent will leave you freezing at the first unfamiliar voice. The best resources mix accents, pace, and register.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">1. iTalki (Customized Travel Lessons)</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">The fastest way to prepare for a trip is to role-play with a native speaker. On iTalki, you can find tutors who specialize in travel English. They can simulate scenarios like clearing customs, reporting a lost passport, or handling a rental car dispute. This builds the muscle memory you need when you are actually on the road.</p>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-300 mb-6">
    <li>Personalized role-play for your specific destination</li>
    <li>Flexible scheduling to fit your pre-trip planning</li>
    <li>Focus on listening to different accents</li>
    <li>Tutors from the UK, US, Canada, Australia, South Africa</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">2. See Guru (Free Trial Before You Buy)</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">If you want to drill travel scenarios without commitment, <a href="/reviews/see-guru/" class="text-emerald-400 hover:text-emerald-300 underline">See Guru</a> gives you three full free lessons with certified teachers, no credit card required. Perfect for last-minute trip prep: tell the tutor your destination and they'll build the lesson around it. After the trial, lessons start at $5, cheaper than most phrasebooks plus audio add-ons.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">3. Duolingo (Vocabulary Foundations)</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">For absolute beginners, Duolingo is a great starting point to build a core vocabulary of travel nouns and verbs. It is free and easy to use during your commute. However, it should be used as a supplement to speaking practice, not a replacement — Duolingo alone will not prepare you to order dinner in a noisy London pub.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">4. Babbel (Dialogue-Based Learning)</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mb-4 leading-relaxed">Babbel offers specific "Travel" modules that focus on realistic dialogues. The speech recognition tool helps you polish your pronunciation so you are understood by locals the first time you speak. The lessons are short (10–15 minutes) and perfect for evening prep sessions.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">5. Rosetta Stone (Immersion Method)</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mb-6 leading-relaxed">Rosetta Stone's immersion approach is especially effective for travel English because it teaches you to associate words with images instead of translations. When you're actually at the airport, you need to recognize signs and situations instantly, not translate them in your head. Not cheap — expect $12–$16/month — but the lifetime subscription deals are worth watching.</p>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">The 4-Week Pre-Trip Plan</h2>
  <ol class="list-decimal list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-300 mb-6">
    <li><strong class="text-white">Week 1:</strong> Duolingo daily (20 min) to rebuild core vocabulary. Watch 2 travel vlogs set in your destination city.</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white">Week 2:</strong> Switch to Babbel travel modules. Start See Guru free trial — one session on "at the airport."</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white">Week 3:</strong> Two more See Guru or iTalki sessions, scenario-based (hotel, restaurant, emergency).</li>
    <li><strong class="text-white">Week 4:</strong> Listening only — podcasts with the destination accent (BBC for UK, NPR for US). Review flash cards.</li>
  </ol>

  <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold mt-10 mb-4 text-white">Verdict</h2>
  <p class="text-gray-300 mb-6 leading-relaxed">Start with Duolingo three months before your trip to build your vocabulary. One month before you leave, book five sessions on iTalki or See Guru to practice your speaking. This approach ensures you have both the words and the confidence to use them. If budget matters, See Guru's three free lessons plus $5 pay-per-lesson rate make this the cheapest serious speaking prep available.</p>

  <div class="bg-gradient-to-br from-emerald-900/50 to-teal-900/40 border-2 border-emerald-600/50 rounded-xl p-8 text-white mt-12 text-center">
    <div class="flex items-center gap-2 justify-center mb-3">
      <span class="text-yellow-400">★★★★★</span>
